GUI using Tkinter 

GUI = Graphical User Interface
It helps you create windows, buttons, apps instead of just text output.

1. What is Tkinter?

Tkinter is Python’s built-in library to create GUI applications.

2. First GUI Program (Window)
Program
import tkinter as tk

window = tk.Tk()
window.title("My App")
window.geometry("300x200")

window.mainloop()
Output

A window opens with title “My App”

3. Add Label (Text)
import tkinter as tk

window = tk.Tk()

label = tk.Label(window, text="Hello Python")
label.pack()

window.mainloop()
Output

Window with text: Hello Python

4. Add Button
import tkinter as tk

window = tk.Tk()

def click():
    print("Button clicked")

button = tk.Button(window, text="Click Me", command=click)
button.pack()

window.mainloop()
Output

Button appears
Clicking prints:

Button clicked

5. Entry Box (User Input)
import tkinter as tk

window = tk.Tk()

entry = tk.Entry(window)
entry.pack()

window.mainloop()
Output

Input box appears

6. Button + Input Example
import tkinter as tk

window = tk.Tk()

entry = tk.Entry(window)
entry.pack()

def show():
    print(entry.get())

button = tk.Button(window, text="Show", command=show)
button.pack()

window.mainloop()
Output

Enter text → click button → prints entered text

7. Mini GUI Project – Simple Calculator
import tkinter as tk

window = tk.Tk()

e1 = tk.Entry(window)
e1.pack()

e2 = tk.Entry(window)
e2.pack()

def add():
    result = int(e1.get()) + int(e2.get())
    print("Sum:", result)

button = tk.Button(window, text="Add", command=add)
button.pack()

window.mainloop()
